descript.abstract:
This data set includes 15cm 4-band [red, green, blue (RGB), and near infrared (IR) portions of the spectrum] digital orthoimagery for Massachusetts in JPEG 2000 format.
The U.S. Geological Survey Massachusetts Orthoimagery project called for the planning, acquisition, processing, and derivative products of imagery data to be collected at a ground sample distance (GSD) of 15cm. Project specifications are based on the American Society of Photogrammetry and Remote Sensing (ASPRS) standards. The data were developed based on a horizontal projection/datum of NAD83 2011 UTM18N, meters and vertical projection/datum NAVD88 (GEOID 12B), meters.
Aerial imagery was collected in spring 2019, in general leaf-off conditions, while no snow was on the ground and rivers were at or below normal levels. The photography was obtained using a Vexcel UltraCam Eagle M1 and M3 digital mapping camera with a flight design that included 183 flight lines of 4-band photography. The flights resulted in 18,269 stereo frame photographs. Aerial imagery was exposed at an altitude of 7,571 feet above mean terrain and was supplemented with the simultaneous acquisition of airborne GPS/IMU data, which captured the ground coordinate for the nadir point of each photograph.
In order to post process the imagery data to meet task order specifications and meet ASPRS horizontal accuracy guidelines, Quantum Spatial, Inc. utilized a total of 132 ground control points to assess the horizontal accuracy of the data. Quantum Spatial provided an Aerial Triangulation Report to USGS.
Orthoimagery data were delivered in 10,218 individual 1500 m x 1500 m tiles as 15cm 16-bit 4-band (RGB-IR) orthophoto tiles in GeoTIFF format. The data span two UTM zones: 4,095 tiles for Zone 18 and 6,123 tiles for Zone 19.
MassGIS converted each GeoTIFF to an 8-bit JPEG 2000 (GMLJP2) format image using GeoExpress 10 software. The JP2 files maintain all four bands and were produced at a lossy compression ratio of 30:1, resulting in very minimal loss of image quality. Each JP2 image is approximately 13 MB, reduced from the 763 MB GeoTIFF, more suitable for distribution and download. MassGIS calculated statistics on the JP2 images in ArcGIS Desktop 10.7.1. All imagery are available for public use and distribution.
This digital orthoimagery can serve a variety of purposes, from general planning, to field reference for spatial analysis, to a tool for data development and revision of vector maps. It can also serve as a reference layer or basemap for myriad applications inside geographic information system (GIS) software and web applications.

attracc.attraccr: Radiometry is verified by visual inspection of the digital orthophoto. Slight systematic radiometric differences may exist between adjacent orthoimage files; these are due primarily to differences in source image capture dates and sun angles along flight lines. These differences can be observed in an image's general lightness or darkness when it is compared to adjacent orthoimage file coverages. Tonal balancing may be performed over a group of images during the mosaicking process which may serve to lighten or darken adjacent images for better color tone matching.

dataqual.logic: All GeoTIFF tagged data and image file sizes are validated using commercial GIS software to ensure proper loading before being archived. This validation procedure ensures correct physical format and field values for tagged elements. Seamlines and tile edges are visually inspected. Seamline mismatches are corrected unless the overall displacement is less than one pixel.
dataqual.complete: Orthoimages are visually inspected for completeness to ensure that no gaps or image misplacements exist within and between adjacent images. These images are derived by mosaicking multiple images to ensure complete coverage. Source imagery is cloud free.

horizpa.horizpar: The project specifications require that only horizontal accuracy be computed for orthoimagery files. The required accuracy meets or exceeds ASPRS standards. The horizontal accuracy was tested with 132 checkpoints located throughout the project area. These checkpoints were not used in the calibration or post-processing of the imagery data. The checkpoints were distributed throughout the project area and were surveyed using GPS techniques. See survey report for additional survey methodologies. The x and y positions of where the checkpoints fell on the orthoimagery were collected. These values were then compared to the surveyed control point x and y values.

qhorizpa.horizpae: Tested 0.1 meters (0.33 feet) RMSEx. The RMSEx of the imagery was calculated using 132 independent checkpoints.
Tested 0.1 meters (0.33 feet) RMSEy. The RMSEy of the imagery was calculated using 132 independent checkpoints.
Tested 0.1 meters (0.33 feet) RMSEr. The RMSEr of the imagery was calculated using 132 independent checkpoints.

vertacc.vertaccr: There is no vertical component for orthophotos.

srcinfo.srccontr: Quantum Spatial performed a geodetic control survey in support of the digital orthophoto production project. A total of 132 points were used for QC testing. Please see the survey report for more information.

Aerial imagery was acquired using an UltraCam Eagle camera with a flight design that included a total of 183 flight lines. Aerial imagery was supplemented with the simultaneous acquisition of airborne GPS/IMU data, which captured the ground coordinate for the nadir point of each photograph. Aerial imagery was exposed at an altitude of 7571 feet above mean terrain.

Softcopy aerotriangulation was performed utilizing the airborne GPS/IMU data, GPS ground control and image coordinate measurements allowing the direct computation of the exterior orientation parameters for each image of the project.
A compilation of topographic land form elevation datasets developed using in-house LiDAR data and data from the National Elevation Dataset for use in developing digital ortho imagery.

procstep.procdesc: Orthophoto Processing: Utilizing all four bands [blue (B), green (G), red (R), and infrared (IR)] digital orthorectification was performed using bilinear interpolation algorithms resulting in a spatial and radiometric transformation of the digital image from line/sample space into NAD83 2011 UTM18N, meters. The interior and exterior orientation parameters from the aerotriangulation process were used to project each pixel into the ground coordinate system, while the ortho grade DEM was used to correct for relief displacement. Radiometric correction software and techniques were used to create orthophoto files that minimize the appearance of image seams and without loss of feature signature. Orthophotos are checked for geometric accuracy, image quality, and are tonally balanced to produce a uniform contrast and tone across the entire project. The individual overlapping orthophoto frames were mosaicked together. The ortho photos meet ASPRS horizontal accuracy standards.

overview.eaover: Four band orthoimagery is organized in four color bands or channels which represent the red, green, blue (RGB), and near infrared (IR) portions of the spectrum. Each image pixel is assigned a quadruplet of numeric values, one for each color band. Numeric values range from 0 to 255.
